<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910501-0040</DOCNO><DOCID>910501-0040.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ogden Corp.:   First-Quarter Net Fell 58%   As Revenue Declined 6.2%</HL><DATE>05/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   OG OPI</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   Ogden Corp., New York, posted a 58% decline infirst-quarter earnings, reflecting a substantial drop in airtravel and a year-earlier special gain from the sale of partof Ogden Projects Inc.   The company said net income fell to $11.6 million, or 27cents a share, from $28 million, or 66 cents a share, a yearearlier. The 1990 results included a gain of $15.6 million,or 37 cents a share, on the sale of stock in Ogden Projects,which is 85% owned by Ogden. Revenue fell 6.2% to $358.3million from $382.1 million.</LP><TEXT>   Ogden, which operates aviation and entertainment supportservices, said the recessionary environment and the severedownturn in the commercial aviation market after the start ofthe Gulf War presented &quot;difficult conditions&quot; for its servicebusinesses, which include aircraft fueling, loading,unloading, and catering.   Quarterly earnings at Ogden Projects, a Fairfield, N.J.,maker of waste-to-energy facilities, rose 39%, to $8.2million, or 22 cents a share, from $5.9 million, or 18 centsa share, a year ago. Revenue fell 9.7%, to $80.2 million from$88.9 million.</TEXT></DOC>